    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nReactant: [H:10][C:11](C)(C)[CH+:20]CCC1=CCCC1\nProduct: [H:10][CH:20](CCC1=CCCC1)[C+:11](C)C\n\nLooking at the atom mapping:\n- H:10 is attached to C:11 in the reactant, and attached to CH:20 in the product\n- C:11 has (C)(C) substituents in both, but in reactant it's connected to CH+:20, and in product it's C+:11\n- CH+:20 in reactant becomes CH:20 in product, and it's connected to CCC1=CCCC1 in both\n\nSo the key change is:\n- In reactant: H:10-C:11-CH+:20 (the H is on C:11, the positive charge is on C:20)\n- In product: H:10-CH:20-C+:11 (the H has moved to C:20, the positive charge has moved to C:11)\n\nThis is a 1,2-hydride shift (or Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement). The H migrates from C:11 to C:20, and the positive charge shifts from C:20 to C:11.\n\nThe reaction center involves:\n- Bond break: C:11-H:10\n- Bond form: C:20-H:10\n- Charge shift: C:20 loses positive charge, C:11 gains positive charge\n\nSo the reaction center is the 1,2-hydride shift from C:11 to C:20, with the H:10 migrating.\n\nLet me format this as a reaction edit summary:\n\nBond changes:\n- Break: C:11-H:10\n- Form: C:20-H:10\n- Charge: C:20 (+1 → 0), C:11 (0 → +1)\n\nThis is essentially a 1,2-hydride shift rearrangement."
